-- Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Afromedia, Fan Milk, KenolKobil, Oceanic Bank
-- Moses Dzawu
-- 2010-07-22T16:20:49Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-22/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-afromedia-kenolkobil-oceanic-bank-tpsea-kenya.html

          
          
             Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  snapped two
days of gains, falling 0.1 percent to close at 1,696.91 as of
1:30 p.m. in Port Louis.  
 Kenya’s  All-Share Index  climbed 0.3 percent to close at
75.82 as of 1:05 p.m. in Nairobi. The  Nigerian Stock Exchange
All-Share Index  rose for a third day, advancing 0.2 percent to
25,056.07 as of the 1 p.m. close in Lagos, while Namibia’s
 FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  climbed 1.7 to 781.9 at the 4 p.m.
close in Windhoek. The  Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share Index  fell
0.4 percent to close at 6,233.04 as of 1 p.m. in Accra, a third
day of declines.  
 The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  
 Afromedia Nigeria Ltd.  (AFROMEDI NL), a Nigerian company
that constructs advertising billboards, fell 3 kobo, or 4.9
percent, to 58 kobo, the lowest since June 28. Profit for the
nine months through June declined 18 percent to 521.1 million
naira, the company said in a statement distributed by the
Nigerian Stock Exchange today.  
 Fan Milk Ltd., a Ghanaian food producer, fell to the lowest
in three months dropping 19 pesewas, or 2.6 percent, to 7 cedis
as Renaissance Capital speculated revenue growth in the second
quarter through June will slow to 5 percent to 25 percent
compared with 65 percent a year earlier, Hilary Lomotey, a
trader with Renaissance, said by phone from Accra today.  
 KenolKobil Ltd.  (KNOC KN), a Kenyan fuel retailer with
operations in seven African countries, rose for the first time
in seven trading days, climbing 15 cents, or 1.5 percent, to
10.2 shillings. Kenya’s Energy Ministry yesterday told Kenya
Petroleum Refineries Ltd. to release fuel stock worth more than
4 billion shillings ($48.8 million) belonging to the fuel
retailer, KenolKobil Chairman  Jacob Segman  said in an e-mailed
statement.  
 Oceanic Bank International Plc  (OCEANIC NL), a Nigerian
lender bailed out by the central bank last year, climbed 8 kobo,
or 4.5 percent, to 1.86 naira, the strongest level in more than
two months. Oceanic has received expressions of interest from
investors who are keen to buy into the bank, Chief Executive
Officer  John Aboh  said in an e-mailed statement yesterday.  
 TPS Eastern Africa Ltd.  (TPSEA KN), the Kenyan holding
company for the Serena Hotel chain in the region, rose 50 cents,
or 0.9 percent, to 59.5 shillings, the highest closing price
since July 15, 2008. TPS will sell 24.7 million shares at 48
cents apiece at a ratio of one share for every five held by
existing shareholders and will use the proceeds to fund
expansion, according to a company statement distributed by the
Nairobi Stock Exchange yesterday.  
